  <main id="main-content" class="art-landing">
    <section class="section-hero hero-fullspan-graphic gradient-bottom art-hero">
      <div class="container-content-vflex width-page-max centered">
        <p class="art-eyebrow">JXL Art</p>
        <div class="wrapper-text color-gradient">
          <h1 class="display-xl-bold fill-gradient">Art Gallery</h1>
        </div>
        <p class="art-lede">
          Procedural images encoded as tiny JPEG XL files. Browse SDR and HDR pieces,
          create your own, or learn how the movement started.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="container-wave-animated">
        <div class="wrapper-content-wave centered align-middle height-cropped-width-full"><img src="/images/Ripple-Line2x-50.0s-2560px-371px.svg" loading="lazy" alt="" class="image-wave-2560"><img src="/images/Ripple-Line2x-50.0s-1440px-300px.svg" loading="lazy" alt="" class="image-wave-1440"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="container-content-vflex width-page-max centered art-hero-actions">
        <div class="art-actions">
          <a class="art-button" href="#about-jxl-art">About JXL Art</a>
          <a class="art-button" href="/art/big_gallery.html">Main Gallery (SDR)</a>
          <a class="art-button" href="/art/hdr.html">HDR Gallery</a>
          <a class="art-button" href="https://jxl-art.lucaversari.it/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Create Your Own</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="art-section flush-top" aria-labelledby="art-featured-heading">
      <div class="art-container">
        <p class="art-eyebrow">Featured</p>
        <h2 id="art-featured-heading" class="art-section-heading">A few tiny showpieces</h2>
        <div class="art-feature-grid">
          <article class="art-feature">
            <img src="/images/art/2022-11-iceberg.jxl" loading="lazy" alt="Iceberg">
            <h3>Iceberg</h3>
            <p>0b5vr, 34 bytes. Winner of the Inercia Demoparty 2022 JXL art compo.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="art-feature">
            <img src="/images/art/2022-11-block_nebula.jxl" loading="lazy" alt="block nebula">
            <h3>block nebula</h3>
            <p>byteobserver, 98 bytes. A compact abstract scene built entirely from JPEG XL tools.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="art-feature">
            <img src="/images/art/2021-08_totocaca.jxl" loading="lazy" alt="Rubin golden vase 1">
            <h3>Rubin golden vase 1</h3>
            <p>totocaca, 81 bytes. A classic example from the August 2021 compo.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="about-jxl-art" class="section-content-wrapper height-100 centered padding-top_bottom">
      <div class="container-content-vflex width-page-max centered">
        <div class="container-content-vflex centered">
          <div class="wrapper-content centered">
            <div class="art-body">
              <p id="jxl-decoder-notice" class="art-jxl-notice" hidden>
                Your browser doesn&rsquo;t support JXL natively, so we&rsquo;re using a local WebAssembly decoder that will be slower than native rendering.
              </p>

              <h2>JXL?</h2>
              <p><a href="/index.html">JPEG XL</a> (aka JXL) is a next-gen image codec designed to replace JPEG and PNG.</p>

              <h2>JXL Art?</h2>
              <p>JXL art is a form of procedural image generation that exploits the powerful meta-adaptive context model (and other coding tools) of JXL to produce interesting-looking images that are tiny JXL files. <a href="https://jxl-art.lucaversari.it/">You can try it yourself here!</a></p>
              <p>If you have made JXL Art yourself, please share it on the <a href="https://discord.gg/DqkQgDRTFu">JXL Discord</a> and perhaps it will be added here!</p>

              <h2>Recent works</h2>
              <p><a href="/art/big_gallery.html">JXL art gallery with source links</a> — SDR pieces with links to the <a href="https://jxl-art.lucaversari.it/">JXL Art</a> tool so you can view, edit, and download the &ldquo;source code&rdquo;. <a href="/art/hdr.html">HDR pieces</a> are on a separate page.</p>

              <h2>History and Early Works</h2>
              <p>The JPEG XL bitstream was finalized in January 2021. It became clear (to its authors) that &ldquo;interesting stuff&rdquo; could be done with tiny JXL files, because of the combination of compact headers, powerful entropy coding, and the MA tree context modeling. Jon Sneyers had already <a href="https://cloudinary.com/blog/compressing_cellular_automata">played with representing cellular automata as MA trees</a> in the context of <a href="https://flif.info/">FLIF</a>, and suggested trying something similar in JXL, noting that JXL&rsquo;s MA trees are even more expressive than FLIF&rsquo;s, and that unlike FLIF&rsquo;s, JXL&rsquo;s entropy coding can encode zero-residual-entropy pixels in literally zero bits. On March 23rd, Luca Versari wrote the <code>jxl_from_tree</code> utility, which was turned into an <a href="https://jxl-art.lucaversari.it/">online tool</a> by Surma. The #jxl-art channel was started on the <a href="https://discord.gg/DqkQgDRTFu">JXL Discord</a>. This was the start of the JXL &ldquo;art movement&rdquo;.</p>
              <p><a href="/art/2021-04_jon.html">Early works by Jon from end of March and April 2021</a> feature a variety of styles and subjects, from very abstract or mathematical to organic and realistic. This first series culminated in this piece <a href="https://jxl-art.lucaversari.it/?zcode=bVRNc5swEL3zK_aclIkkDLZ76EySSZtDhnaSznBWbAU0AURAjuN_X60-QHFzQmif3r59u9KN1Hsx6AYoSX6PUvSaa6l6WCeV3JttRlab5F7IutEGwlbJ4-1fKJLrdmh48nPknfijJkiLgkFKCUmuLmA3qmEC3QiQvdQwquME_MhP34D3exj4qEG92PgkOGgFtdDAgX3PgE-D2JkjqAEurpKkVPqBTxoM7VHAUbYtqHcxtvwEk-qEbmRfg5Gr1eBI5WTPyRfYwQ9gSQpPwirPkEMN_O0g4LkGwyBGCzXbt82oOo5__hwJC4qLGpmop0pzG_wweyu7qtKqMj8pAqrwIR6dERIx-HPEISN1BhWCRe7Cl5CFjFsMG5kPh1nkCQmt20-vJ-trpw6md7KfPOI8JSr9dW-WSHv9XpeXJSbJMVBWaYkl5ITMwTsjMDd_FkUB3RMfWkSZgnu2y-fpLV9BLGGJtQZHUlctKhehGlRICc29gyRSS2O1LFbHEsvyaIpXXS-m_wvHtjg37fyKPXIHz5nP4ur-BFp5DNrhkrSqVn5klmEzVZuMeB9c91xiO2Z9ezK22BlHsJ35ZbqYdRODlteMrMdyvFVRh_NibmBBqWtGNClkG4BFtgnLDQ2TuiKhWNuEu-UTsOTTeLguMDaHGVvPBH5rTb4gP9PoE1VRoohoOR6ObRmL0-BWNrPnZNH2NQu-OKpVY3hUrKfxVV4umbX9ML4dlJwEYuYKTKBX7jXxvXhWWqtubl1A_gM">(&ldquo;source code&rdquo;)</a> from April 23rd, 2021:</p>

              <h3>Tropical Island Sunset with JXL logo overlay</h3>
              <p class="art-caption">2021, Jon Sneyers, image/jxl, 218 bytes</p>
              <img src="data:image/jxl;base64,/wraHNTQIGACCJitkOMAHsBAAAB8AQAAQAAEAAuAo21bLaPKyBwPmAAmM/03iRCZjVBUzAilhVqNiIdCcBpMEbiPPg8So43fsXQxjmKEXqbFg0GLk7/d/PkRitc4BCtg8Xlt9FQmeAITz2vFOPuMz4+VMCZYSkCScAAAAwMImK2Q4wAewESiAAAcAQAAQAAEAAuAi2UrKor1RkxDgFBgxeZDMX4rMCb0q/qgOlIYoHnwNz+nVsB/CywPlidcVj7p3xhjtIhBoufAwQ/Swyxj2UWAo4IEKUkYAwM=" alt="Tropical Island Sunset with JXL logo overlay">

              <h2>Animation and Splines</h2>
              <p>More features were added to the <code>jxl_from_tree</code> utility. Jon added support for animation and blend modes in May 2021. Sami Boukortt added <a href="https://github.com/libjxl/libjxl/pull/247">support for splines</a> on June 29th. With splines, smooth curves can be drawn easily, which nicely complements what can be achieved with MA trees.</p>
              <img src="/images/art/anim_jxl_logo.jxl" alt="Animated JXL logo">

              <h2>JXL Art Compos</h2>
              <h3>Inércia Demoparty 2022</h3>
              <p>In November 2022, a compo was organized at the <a href="https://2022.inercia.pt/">Inércia Demoparty 2022</a>.</p>
              <p><strong>First place:</strong></p>
              <h3>Iceberg</h3>
              <p class="art-caption">2022, 0b5vr, image/jxl, 34 bytes</p>
              <img src="/images/art/2022-11-iceberg.jxl" alt="Iceberg">
              <p><strong>Second place:</strong></p>
              <h3>block nebula</h3>
              <p class="art-caption">2022, byteobserver, image/jxl, 98 bytes</p>
              <img src="/images/art/2022-11-block_nebula.jxl" alt="block nebula">
              <p><strong>Third place:</strong></p>
              <h3>JXL</h3>
              <p class="art-caption">2022, _wb_, image/jxl, 352 bytes</p>
              <img src="/images/art/2022-11-jxl.jxl" alt="JXL">

              <h3>August 2021 Compo</h3>
              <p>In August 2021, a competition was held in the #jxl-art channel on the JXL Discord.</p>
